<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-09-30T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-09-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="132" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d132">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.03/9–3046: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-09-30">September 30,
                                1946</date>.<lb/>[Received October 1—3:48 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1564. Communist spokesman Nanking September 30 announced Communist
                            delegation September 29 formally rejected Government request to submit
                            names of delegates to National Assembly scheduled to convene November
                            12. Spokesman said rejection was sent in letter to Chang Li Sheng, head
                            of National Assembly election department, which also stated Communists
                            could not participate since decision to hold assembly was taken
                            unilaterally rather than through inter-party consultations in accordance
                            with P.C.C.<note n="10" xml:id="d132fn10">Political Consultative
                                Conference.</note> resolutions.</p>
                        <p>Democratic League representative has informed United Press the League
                            will take a similar stand.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>